Technological advancements have changed the look and functionalities of the control room, however, the complexity often caused by these technologies can, and indeed have, dramatically affected safety and performance. Therefore, it is important to understand the tasks and functionalities of these technologies as well as the cognitive demands imposed on the operators.2 After a number of accidents (e.g. Three Mile Island) human factors assessments became a mandatory precursor to the development of control rooms (new or modified technologies), railways is no exception. Often methods used by engineers and human factors specialists to achieve this understanding include workload assessment, human error evaluation, and task analysis. One significant human factors contribution to rail systems design over the past few years has been to carry out work analyses. Such work analyses are particularly important in process and transport control systems which collect data remotely from complex environments. The analyses determine:


what tasks/functions must be carried out in what circumstances, in order to support decisions on what human and computer resources are required;

how these should be integrated into an effective work system;

how information display interfaces should be designed (for form and content);

what human roles and crew sizes are needed;

what loading might be placed on operators in normal, abnormal and emergency scenarios.
